<br>
But the discussion often reaches a deadlock.  It difficult if not impossible to compare the utility a melee brings to a group to that brought by a caster.  What is the value of tanking, for example, and how does it compare to mezz?<br>
<br>
I think most players would probably agree that the priest classes, except possibly druid, are fairly well balanced, or at least not in need of dramatic improvement.  Assuming, for the sake of discussion, that clerics and shaman are largely balanced, how do pure casters in general and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in specific compare to priest classes?<br>
<br>
I will begin with a few observations.<br>
<br>
First, priest classes are physically more secure than casters, having better armor, more hitpoints, and some melee ability.  How significant is this, or might as well they be robe-wearers for all it matters?<br>
<br>
Second, priest classes have tremendous and obvious utility, including heals, slows, and buffs.  While generally they are not considered damage dealers, especially clerics, they can act as plausible damage dealers in a pinch, and druid nukes are arguably better than <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
I suggest that comparing casters to priests might reveal important issues that do not arise from comparing ourselves to melees.  Priests are much more like us in terms of spells, gear dependency, and so on, but are utility centered rather than damage centered.<br>
<br>
I look forward to everyone's thoughtful responses and ideas.<br>
<br>
